  _h_t_t_p_s_:_/_/_e_n_._w_i_k_i_p_e_d_i_a_._o_r_g_/_w_i_k_i_/_I_n_d_o_n_e_s_i_a_%_E_2_%_8_0_%_9_3_P_a_p_u_a___N_e_w___G_u_i_n_e_a___b_o_r_d_e_r_ 

  The Netherlands began colonising the area of modern Indonesia (then called the
  Dutch East Indies) in the 17th century, and extended their rule eastwards. In 1828
  they claimed the north-west coast of New Guinea as far as the 140th meridian east
  in 1828, as part of the traditional lands of the Sultan of Tidore.[2] In 1884 the
  north-eastern quarter of New Guinea was claimed by Germany and the south-eastern
  quarter by Britain, with the two agreeing a border between their respective
  territories the following year.[2] In 1895 Britain and the Netherlands signed a
  border treaty which delimited their common boundary on the island at its current
  location.
